LD END--> rather than the rule (which is as far as I can tell, is what people want: a generally coherant and consistent set of guidelines about who is opposed to who, with a few rare exceptions).<br>
<br>
Are there players who come up with great, ironclad storylines behind why they associate with the &quot;type of people&quot; that their race or class is normally opposed to?  Sure.  However, those who are genuine about it tend to be the sort of diehard roleplayers who are willing to sacrifice a few conveniences for their unorthodox roleplay point of view.<br>
<br>
There was a time when the FV server was my absolute favorite, and I couldn't imagine playing anywhere else.  Now Firiona Vie is a normal server with a 1 character per account limit and TLC.  Considering the fact that I never was a big fan of TLC (and now I outright hate it now that I'm of a level where it's simply closed off a few quests I wanted to do), all that Firiona Vie that really has going for it now is a something of a community atmosphere that's lacking on most other servers.  I guess that's nice, but it has really very little to do with roleplaying.<br>
<br>
I think the alignment grouping system we had before was just fine for encouraging and sticking to roleplay.  I think that with that, and the 1 character limit, we'd be fine, even without the easily surmountable communications barrier, even without TLC (which never really had anything to do with RPing), even without forced /rp, even with zonewide /shout and an /ooc channel.<br>
<br>
I don't see the rules changing (except perhaps to make Firiona Vie even more &quot;normal&quot; as Verant realizes their experiment has failed) so I guess this is just sour grapes.  Firiona Vie is what sparked my interest in EQ again, and now it's changes to Firiona Vie that have been slowly smothering and killing my interest in EQ. <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
